Assume that reneging would provoke the exclusion of the buyer.

Exclusion: loss of the continuation payoff V^b associated with future trades.

V^b obtains from stationarity:V^b = \sigma U^b + \frac{V^b}{1+r}

where r is the discount rate of the buyer.

Solving in V^b:V^b = \frac{\sigma U^b(1+r)}{r} = \frac{\sigma(1+r)}{r}[u(q)-y]

Result

Buyer honours an obligation to pay the seller whenever the payment y is lower than the discounted continuation pay-off \frac{V^b}{1+r}:y \leq \frac{V^b}{1+r}

↓y\leq \frac{\sigma u (q)}{r+\sigma}

Comparing with no friction outcoume\to set of feasible transactions is strictly smallerc(q)\leq y \leq \frac{\sigma u (q)}{r+\sigma} \leq u(q)

ConclusionEven in a close-knit community, the impossibility to commit reduces the set of feasible transactions.

Platform sets fees to maximizes profits

Start by differentiating profit w.r.t. a_b (buyer fee):\frac{\partial \Pi}{\partial a_b}
    = N_s\Big[N_b + (a_b+a_s-c)N_b'(u_b)\frac{\partial u_b}{\partial a_b}\Big]

with \frac{\partial u_b}{\partial a_b}=-n_s.

Set to zero and isolate fees and costs:N_s\Big[N_b + (a_b+a_s-c)N_b'(u_b)(-n_s)\Big] = 0\\
    \\
    \rightarrow 
    \frac{1}{a_b+a_s-c} = -\frac{N_b'(u_b)}{N_b(u_b)}\,n_s

Define semi-elasticity in utility space:\varepsilon_b^{u} = -\frac{N_b'(u_b)}{N_b(u_b)}u_b

where: u_b = (\beta_b - a_b)\, n_s\rightarrow \varepsilon_b^{u} = -\frac{N_b'(u_b)\,(\beta_b - a_b)\, n_s}{N_b(u_b)} \quad \leftrightarrow \frac{\varepsilon_b^{u}}{\beta_b-a_b} = -\frac{N_b'(u_b)}{N_b(u_b)}\,n_s

Plug elasticity expression in previous expression:\boxed{\frac{1}{a_b+a_s-c} = \frac{\varepsilon_b^{u}}{\beta_b-a_b}}

By symmetry for the seller fee:\boxed{\frac{1}{a_b+a_s-c} = \frac{\varepsilon_s^{u}}{\beta_s-a_s}}

Express condition in terms of fee elasticities

Define fee elasticity:\eta_b^{a} = -\frac{N_b'(u_b)}{N_b(u_b)}\frac{\partial u_b}{\partial a_b}\,a_b

Since \partial u_b/\partial a_b = -n_s, we get:\eta_b^{a} = \frac{N_b'(u_b)}{N_b(u_b)}\,n_s\,a_b = \frac{a_b}{\beta_b-a_b}\,\varepsilon_b^{u}

Plug back:\boxed{a_b+a_s-c = \frac{a_b}{\eta_b^{a}}}

Similarly:\boxed{a_b+a_s-c = \frac{a_s}{\eta_s^{a}}}

Limited liability: Let D be the repayment due in success and nothing is paid in failure.

Expected payoff\mathbb{E}[w] = 
\begin{cases}
 p_H (R_H - D) ~~ &\text{if} ~~ e=1\\ 
p_L (R_L - D) + B~~ &\text{if} ~~ e=0
\end{cases}
